Kim Kitsuragi: "We should get moving. Running gets the endorphines going, no?" He smiles at his own remark, then takes in the damp air.

Visual Calculus: A luminous wheel of pleasure and all things bright, its wooden frame creaking in the wind. Twelve red cabins form a circle that stretches from the engines below to the flocks of seagulls up in the sky.
Inland Empire: The mirage looks both sad and glorious in the mist, like an insect trapped in glass.
Inland Empire: Some sadness comes crashing over you like a bad dream.
Kim Kitsuragi: "But I don't think standing here in the cold is doing you or me any good. Let's go. We've got a case to solve."

Visual Calculus: There's a ticket office made out of an old gondola, its wooden frame the same shade of red as the ones above. A sign mounted on its side declares: "TWENTY CENTIMS FOR THE RIDE OF A LIFETIME!"
You: Study the cabins.
Visual Calculus: The little wooden gondolas dangle in the wind, their seats empty and floors littered with old ice cream papers and discarded tickets...
Perception: A seabird has made a nest in one of the cabins, but even this looks abandoned -- a remnant from a spring some fifty odd years ago.
Shivers: The wind gets stronger the higher you go. On a good day you could see all the way to La Delta when you reached the top -- and the masts and sails of dozens of pleasure crafts.
You: Step back. [Leave.]
Visual Calculus: Some waves come crashing against the boardwalk, shattering the mirage.
Kim Kitsuragi: "The man we found?" He realises that neither of you knows his name. "Yes, I don't know... We didn't learn much about him, did we?"
You: "Do you think he enjoyed his last moments out here? Do you think he was having *fun*?"
You: "I don't know. I don't know what's going on with me. Something's coming apart."
